{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="6123-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">Error 6123, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Error 6123, 0 appears when QuickBooks Desktop can&rsquo;t open or restore the company file because the connection to that file is broken. You most often see it while opening a file, restoring a backup, or opening a file stored on another computer over a network &mdash; and it commonly shows up immediately after a Windows or QuickBooks update, or after a file has been moved or restored across machines. The error is QuickBooks telling you it reached for the file and the path to it failed, whether that&rsquo;s a network/hosting issue, a security program blocking access, a version or restore mismatch, or genuine damage to the file or its supporting .ND/.TLG files.</p>
      <p>The good news is that Error 6123 is highly fixable, and the self-fix steps below work in order of likelihood &mdash; running QuickBooks Tool Hub (Quick Fix My File, then File Doctor) resolves it in many cases before deeper troubleshooting is needed. If self-fix doesn&rsquo;t resolve it within an hour or two, or the error recurs within days, a Certified ProAdvisor diagnostic identifies the deeper cause &mdash; typically configuration or file-integrity damage past the documented surface steps. Error 6123 is a QuickBooks Desktop and Enterprise error; it does not appear in QuickBooks Online.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

